(56, 'Jaundice', 'Jaundice is a disorder in which the skin, white areas of the eyes, and mucous membranes turn yellow in color. It is caused by the accumulation of bilirubin. Bilirubin is a waste product created during the typical breakdown of hemoglobin. It moves through the liver before ultimately being eliminated from the body. Inadequate elimination or increased production lead to excessive bilirubin. Some possible causes of jaundice include liver disease like cirrhosis or hepatitis, gallstones, alcohol consumption, gallbladder cancer, which is a disease that or other liver infections, and anemia. The normal blood levels of bilirubin are less than 1 mg/dl. When the bilirubin level increases above 3 mg/dl, it results in jaundice. As the serum bilirubin levels increase, the skin will progressively discolor, ranging from yellow to green. The green color is due to biliverdin, which is also a by-product of hemoglobin.', ''),
(57, 'Kidney Stones', 'The kidney is the organ that removes waste products from the body in the form of urine. It is an important part of the urinary system. In kidney stones, the waste product gets struck in the urinary system. Kidney stone symptoms include severe pain in the side or back of the abdomen, associated with nausea and difficulty urinating. Although passing kidney stones can be extremely painful, if they are caught early enough, they typically don\'t result in permanent harm. You might only need to take painkillers and drink a lot of water to clear a kidney stone, depending on your circumstances. Although passing kidney stones can be extremely painful, if they are caught early enough, they typically don\'t result in permanent harm. You might only need to take painkillers and drink a lot of water to clear a kidney stone, depending on your circumstances.', 'Y'),
(58, 'Malaria', 'Malaria is a disease caused by a mosquito known as the female Anopheles mosquito. The parasite is spread to humans through the bites of infected mosquitoes. The attack of mosquitoes causes damage to the red blood cells, typically causing a high fever with chills and other symptoms that may develop into life-threatening complications. Hence, timely diagnosis and treatment of malaria are very crucial. When a person gets malaria, symptoms often start to appear 10–30 days after infection. The severity of the symptoms can vary depending on the parasite species. Some people experience no symptoms for up to a year following a mosquito bite. Sometimes parasites can remain dormant in the body for years without showing any signs. Malaria is typically diagnosed through blood tests. ', 'Y'),
(59, 'Pneumonia', 'Pneumonia is a lung disease. It makes breathing challenging and lowers the body\'s oxygen levels. Microbes like bacteria, viruses, and fungi are the main causes of it. In pneumonia, the air pouches that are normally filled with air during breathing are instead filled with fluid. In other words, a pneumonia patient\'s lungs are filled with fluid instead of air. This may result in symptoms like coughing, fever, breathlessness, and chest pain. Pneumonia primarily affects children under the age of two and the elderly over the age of fifty. Diagnosis can be done by chest X-ray, CT scan, blood analysis, and sputum analysis. Most cases of pneumonia can be treated with oral antibiotics. Even if you start to feel better, always finish your prescription of antibiotics.', 'Y'),
(60, 'Rickets', 'A prevalent medical disease affecting children is rickets. Symptoms of rickets include a twisted spine and bowed legs, which are painful and uncomfortable. A child may get rickets that is either hereditary (with a genetic basis) or acquired, depending on the type. Rickets has mostly been linked to a deficiency of vitamin D, calcium, and phosphorus. Rickets risk can also be increased by other factors, like living in a cold climate, and having dark skin. In most cases, rickets is related to bone issues, and it can be resolved by increasing calcium or vitamin D intake. A child may need more medicine or other treatments if the underlying medical condition that is causing the rickets requires other therapy. Some rickets-related skeletal abnormalities may need surgery to be corrected.', ''),
(61, 'Scabies', 'Scabies is a contagious, itchy skin disease caused by a tick bite. The most common sign of scabies is severe scratching where the mites have made their burrows. Scabies is caused by an eight-legged female mite. The female mite burrows just under the skin and makes a tunnel where it lays eggs. Scabies can be treated by applying medication from the neck down and leaving it on for eight hours, which will kill the mites and their eggs. Oral medications are another option for killing the mites. Maintaining hygiene and cleanliness can prevent scabies. Permethrin cream and malathion lotion are the two most popular treatments for scabies. Both drugs include insecticides in them that eliminate the scabies mite. ', 'Y'),
(62, 'Typhoid fever', 'Typhoid is an intestinal infection caused by bacteria. Salmonella typhi is the bacteria responsible for long-lasting typhoid. In places with poor access to sanitary facilities and clean water, it is very common. Diabetes is spread through human-to-human contact. It typically spreads through contaminated food and water that have been touched by the feces of an infected person. Symptoms of typhoid include high fever, headache, stomach ache, weakness, vomiting, and loose stools. Antibiotics are used to treat typhoid fever, and in the majority of instances, prompt treatment assures a speedy recovery. It can result in problems that are life-threatening if left untreated. Most cases of typhoid can be avoided by practicing excellent hygiene and drinking clean water. Typhoid vaccination is also offered, but it has a mediocre level of efficacy.', 'Y'),
(63, 'Vertigo', 'Vertigo is a condition in which a person starts feeling unbalanced and dizzy. A person could experience a sense of dizziness or the impression that everything around them is spinning. Vertigo can develop as a result of an inner ear disturbance or from other balance-impairing head and neck problems. The inner ear plays an important role in balancing the head in its position by maintaining pressure on both sides. There are two types of vertigo: peripheral and central. Peripheral vertigo is caused by problems in the inner ear. Central vertigo is caused by a brain or vestibulocochlear nerve defect. These vertigo attacks are frequently brief and don\'t need any medical attention because they go away on their own. Treatment is necessary, though, if the episodes persist or become so severe that they interfere with the patient\'s regular activities.', 'Y'),
(64, 'Wilson\'s Disease', 'Wilson\'s disease is a genetic disorder characterized by an accumulation of copper in the body. It is caused by changes in the ATP7B gene present on chromosome 13, which produces a protein called copper transporting protein. This protein is crucial for moving copper from the liver to the rest of the body. It also aids in the body\'s removal of extra copper. Wilson\'s illness most frequently manifests as liver disease. Symptoms also include tremor, muscle stiffness, drooling, trouble speaking, poor motor coordination, abrupt personality changes, neurosis, and psychosis, which are caused by nervous system involvement or mental alterations. The patient\'s body accumulates toxic quantities of copper, particularly in the liver and brain, which increases your risk of organ damage. Your mood will be impacted by elevated copper levels, which frequently leave you feeling weak, uncomfortable, and in pain. It is advised to seek help from doctors if you experience weakness, exhaustion, or persistent pain.', ''),
(65, 'Dengue', 'Dengue is a viral disease caused by a mosquito bite. When a healthy individual is bitten by an Aedes mosquito carrying the dengue virus, especially during the day, the person gets dengue. Dengue cannot be spread through contact, coughing, or secretions. High-grade fever, eye pain, skin rash, headache, body aches, and joint pain are all symptoms of dengue. Dengue fever is typically a moderate illness that can be treated at home by maintaining fluid intake, keeping an eye on symptoms, and using medications. But occasionally, it could result in a potentially harmful complication known as severe dengue (hemorrhage and shock). Severe dengue can cause bleeding, excruciating abdominal pain, and difficulty breathing. Dengue hemorrhagic fever is thought to be more likely to infect people with weak immune systems, as well as those who have experienced a second or subsequent dengue infection.', ''),
(66, 'Ascitis', 'Ascitis is an abnormal accumulation of fluid inside the cavities of the abdomen. The illness is secondary to liver cirrhosis, which is primarily brought on by consuming large amounts of alcohol. Ascitis is also seen in advanced stages of cancer and recurring malignancies, infections, clotting in blood vessels, low protein levels, and dialysis. Depending on the cause of the ascites, symptoms may appear gradually or quickly. The earliest sign of ascites is swelling of the abdomen, bloating, and pain in the swollen region. Breathlessness can result from large fluid accumulations because the fluid presses up on the diaphragm, which in turn compresses the lower lungs. If there is only a small amount of fluid in the belly, one might not experience any symptoms. The doctor suggests ultrasound, urine analysis, and liver function tests to confirm the diagnosis of ascitis. Acitis can be prevented by avoiding alcohol and limiting salt intake in the daily diet.', ''),
(67, 'Bronchitis', 'Bronchi are a component of the respiratory system. An inflammation of the bronchial tube lining is known as bronchitis. It manifests symptoms like frequent coughing with or without mucus, shortness of breath, exhaustion, fever, and wheezing or whistling noises when breathing. Bronchitis is generally caused by a bacterial or viral infection. Other causes of bronchitis include an allergic reaction to smoke or another irritant or allergen. Bronchitis can be of two types: acute and chronic. Acute bronchitis is a minor illness, like the seasonal virus flu associated with allergies. Chronic bronchitis is a severe form of bronchitis and is associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). The frequent causes of chronic bronchitis are smoking and prolonged exposure to air pollution. Bronchitis can create further complications due to a weak immune system in the patient. Bronchitis patients are usually given antiviral and anti-inflammatory medicines.', 'Y'),
(68, 'Chickenpox', 'Chickenpox is a viral infection disease.The varicella-zoster virus is the cause of chickenpox. Varicella-Zoster Virus is also known as the chickenpox virus. It is a highly contagious illness, which means it can spread from one person to another. It primarily affects children but can also affect adults. It is often a mild, self-limiting illness, but in infants or people with weakened immune systems, it can cause serious health problems. Symptoms of chickenpox are typical: extremely itchy rashes, flu, loss of appetite, headache, and chills. Home remedies and at-home care choices can help to reduce the discomfort and itching of chickenpox, even though the symptoms progress at their own pace. Once the chickenpox rash appears, it goes through three phases. Raised red bumps known as papules, which stay over for several days. The second phase is small, fluid-filled blisters, which form in about one day and then break and leak pus. The third phase is about crusts and scabs, which cover the broken blisters and take several more days to heal. These rashes and symptoms of chickenpox last for 10–15 days and gradually heal themselves.', 'Y'),
(69, 'Dysyntery', 'Dysentery is a painful infection of the intestine. It results in loose, watery feces that contain blood and mucous. Other symptoms include fever, nausea, belly cramps, weight loss, and a swollen liver. It is a very contagious illness brought on by germs or parasites. The likelihood of developing the disease is increased by inadequate sanitation, poor hand hygiene, eating or drinking food or water contaminated with feces, and a number of other factors. Dysentery is most often caused by Shigella bacteria or an amoeba. People typically do not require treatment for dysentery because it usually goes away on its own in 3 to 7 days. If the person has diarrhea, they should drink enough water to prevent dehydration. They should refrain from taking anti-diarrheal medicine if the diarrhea is bloody. In the event that diarrhea and other symptoms are severe, a doctor might advise antibiotics.', ''),
(70, 'Fatty liver disease', 'Fatty liver disease is a type of liver disease that can be caused by excessive alcohol use. In the early stages of FLD, the majority of people are unaware that they have it. It only exhibits symptoms or signs when liver failure progresses to that point. Type 2 diabetes and obesity are two major risk factors for FLD, while excessive alcohol also plays a key role. Typically, it has no symptoms. Fatigue, weight loss, and abdominal pain are among the symptoms that might appear. Through a diet and exercise regimen, the risk factors, such as obesity, are reduced as part of the treatment. Although it is mostly benign, in a small number of patients, it can lead to liver failure (cirrhosis).', ''),
(71, 'Gallstones', 'Gallstones are also known as cholelithiasis. Fragments of solid, stone-like particles accumulate in the bile duct or gallbladder, causing gall bladder stones. These gallstones, which are typically composed of cholesterol or bilirubin (a red-yellow pigment), can cause an abrupt, excruciating discomfort in the belly. Some people may experience the development of a single, massive gallstone, while others may experience the development of multiple, smaller gallstones. Symptoms may include pain in the right upper belly, pain in the right shoulder or back, an upset stomach, vomiting, and other digestive problems like indigestion, heartburn, and gas. The tests used to diagnose gallstones include blood tests and ultrasound imaging of the abdomen. Small gallstones are not even detectable and do not show any signs. However, large stones cause unbearable pain and require surgery to remove the stone.', 'Y'),
(72, 'HIV (human immunodeficiency virus)', 'The human immunodeficiency virus causes AIDS. AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome) affects the body\'s immune system. HIV infection shows flu-like symptoms or no symptoms at all in the first two weeks. This HIV infection is referred to as primary or acute. It is followed by a dormant stage, in which the virus multiplies but rarely manifests any symptoms or indicators. In the third week, the patient experiences severe fever and weight loss. The virus gradually weakens the immune system and develops into AIDS. HIV infection spreads through sexual contact or blood transfusion from the infected person. HIV-positive pregnant women can pass the infection on to their unborn child due to their shared blood circulation. Although there is no cure for HIV/AIDS, drugs can manage the virus and stop the disease\'s progression if noticed at an early stage.', 'Y'),
(73, 'Liver Cirrhosis', 'The scarring (fibrosis) of the liver that results from chronic liver injury is called cirrhosis. The liver cannot function properly because of the scar tissue. It develops after earlier stages of liver damage from illnesses like hepatitis. Cirrhosis is sometimes referred to as an end-stage liver disease. Cirrhosis patients may initially have little or no symptoms or indicators of liver disease. Some of the symptoms, such as weakness, exhaustion, nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite with weight loss, may be general in nature. But as the condition worsens, more severe side effects could appear, including tiny spider-like veins under the skin, intense itching, bleeding or bruising, jaundice, edema (swelling of the legs, ankles, and feet), ascites (a painful swelling of the stomach caused by a buildup of fluid), and confusion. Treatment of cirrhosis depends on treating the underlying cause. In severe cases, a liver transplant is required.', ''),
(74, 'Migraine', 'Migraine is a disorder that primarily affects one or both sides of the head and is characterized by severe and unprovoked headaches. It differs from a typical headache in that it comes with extra signs like nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. Although the precise cause of migraines is unknown, it is believed that transitory alterations in the brain\'s neurotransmitters, neurons, and blood vessels are to blame. Nearly half of all migraine sufferers also have a close family relative who has the disorder, which raises the possibility that genes may be involved. Hormonal changes, particular foods and drinks, stress, and exercise are triggers. One specific location may throb to varying degrees during a migraine headache. Others include nausea and sensitivity to light and sound. Medication for pain relief and prevention can help manage migraines.', 'Y'),
(75, 'Neonatal Jaundice', 'Neonatal jaundice is also known as infant jaundice or neonatal hyperbilirubinemia. It is caused due to elevated total serum bilirubin (TSB), which shows symptoms like yellowish discoloration of the skin, mucous membranes, and sclera(the white coating covering the inner surface of the eye). About two-thirds of all healthy neonates have this problem and it is fairly common. It can, however, occasionally indicate improper dietary patterns, hydration levels, or red blood cell life span (RBCs). Infrequent reasons can also include liver illness, metabolic abnormalities, and glandular issues. But in most cases, it is physiologically normal and disappears after few days. Neonatal jaundice can also cause further problems if left untreated. Possible complication include kernicterus and Acute bilirubin encephalopathy. The best defence against neonatal jaundice is proper nutrition. Breast-fed newborns require eight to twelve feedings daily. ', ''),
(76, 'Osteoporosis', 'Osteoporosis means porous bone. Bone fragility and fracture risk are increased by this disorder. Osteoporosis is known as the \"silent disease of the bones\" since patients don\'t experience any symptoms until a bone fracture occurs. These spontaneous fractures may result in severe back discomfort, height loss, or spinal deformities such as kyphosis (hunched posture). Osteoporosis is frequently encountered in elderly women, mainly due to menopause. An elderly woman lacks estrogen, a hormone responsible for female reproduction. Estrogen also helps to maintain bone density, and the lack of the hormone after menopause makes the bones fragile and prone to fractures. Other important risk factors include family history, inactivity, a lack of calcium and vitamin D, smoking, binge drinking, and low body weight. X-rays are used to diagnose osteoporosis. The severity of the illness typically dictates the course of treatment. It\'s crucial to make lifestyle changes like avoiding jerky movements, taking calcium and vitamin D supplements, and giving up smoking. In severe cases, prescription medicines and hormone therapy may be necessary.', 'Y'),
(77, 'Polio', 'Polio is also known as poliomyelitis. It is caused by a virus called Poliovirus. The virus that causes polio, damages the spinal cord or brain stem nerves. In its most severe form, polio can cause paralysis (the inability to move particular limbs). Additionally, it may cause respiratory difficulties and even death. Polio virus gets transmitted by faecal- oral route. Polio can be non-paralytic or paralytic in nature depending on its severity. Non- paralytic polio shows flu like symptoms in phase 1. Phase 2 of the disorder includes symptoms like muscle weakness, decreased reflexes and stiffness over spinal area.  Paralytic polio is the most severe form of polio. Intense pain in spine and neck, extreme sensitivity to touch, pricking sensations, muscl/es spasms or twitching and ultimately resulting in limp paralysis.If remained untreated, polio might cause permanent paralysis, bones or joints deformity and Post-polio syndrome like sleep apnea, breathing problems and muscle wasting. Polio can be prevented by active immunization or vaccination which is given by the age of 5 years old.', ''),
(78, 'Q fever', 'Q fever is a disease that spreads from animals to people. The bacterium Coxiella burnetii causes Q fever. The bacteria is primarily found in cattle, sheep, and goats. Therefore, the bacterium can be found in the affected animal\'s milk, urine, and feces. In humans, it is brought on by inhaling dust that has been contaminated by diseased animals. When animals give birth, their byproducts, like placenta, get contaminated by bacteria, and when they get dry, they contaminate the air. Agriculture, veterinary care, and animal research are among the high-risk professions for Q fever. Symptoms like fever, cough, nausea, and exhaustion appear in the patient. The heart, lungs, liver, brain, and other vital organs may suffer severe damage if the Q fever lingers for a long time. Avoiding close contact with animals while they are giving birth and maintaining proper hygiene at work will help prevent the sickness (in farms and barnyards).', ''),
(79, 'Rabies', 'Rabies is a viral disease typically transmitted by an animal bite, such as one from a stray dog. Fever, headaches, excessive salivation, muscle spasms, paralysis, and confusion are some symptoms of rabies. Seek emergency medical assistance immediately after an animal bite. For rabies, there is no particular treatment. Once symptoms start, it almost always ends in death unless you\'re vaccinated. Animals that can transmit rabies are street dogs, cats, bats, coyotes, foxes, monkeys, racoons, horses, and goats. Rabies can also be transmitted when contaminated saliva contacts an open wound or mucous membranes, such as the mouth or eyes. Vaccinating pets and avoiding animal bites are the two greatest ways to prevent the spread of rabies. Children should receive proper rabies education and dog protection. Pre-exposure vaccinations are also advised for those at high risk, such as veterinarians, researchers studying the rabies virus, and those who work with wild animals.', ''),
(80, 'Sepsis', 'A life-threatening illness known as sepsis or septicemia occurs when the body begins to harm its own tissues in reaction to an infection. Any type of infection— bacterial, viral or fungal, can lead to sepsis. Infections that can result in sepsis include infections of lungs, kidney, bladder and other parts of the urinary system, digestive system, blood, sites of catheterization, wounds or burns. Symptoms of sepsis include rapid reduction in blood pressure, organ failure, or even death. Infants and elderly people are at higher risk of developing sepsis. Sepsis is more likely to affect people whose immune systems have been damaged by illnesses like diabetes, chronic renal disease, or liver disease. Antibiotics, intravenous fluids, and vasopressors are all used to treat sepsis (drugs constricting blood vessels). Sepsis patients may also need supportive treatment, such as oxygen or a breathing machine. The likelihood of recovering from septicemia is increased by prompt and intensive therapy. Sepsis patients typically need to be treated at a hospital\'s intensive care unit.', ''),
(81, 'Thalassemia', 'Thalassemia is a genetic disorder. It is a condition where a person\'s body produces less hemoglobin than normal. Hemoglobin is an oxygen-carrying protein. Because of hemoglobin, red blood cells can carry oxygen. Anemia is a symptom of thalassemia. A patient with this disease might not need therapy if he or she has mild thalassemia. However, more serious conditions could require frequent blood transfusions. Thalassemia minor is a term used to describe a person who has mild thalassemia symptoms. However, a person is said to have thalassemia major if they have moderate to severe symptoms. Even if a person does not exhibit any signs of thalassemia, they may still be a carrier for the condition. Thalassemia is typically unpreventable. If you wish to have children but have thalassemia or carry the thalassemia gene, you should consider speaking with a genetic counselor for advice. An early-stage embryo is checked for genetic abnormalities using assisted reproductive technologies in conjunction with in vitro fertilization. This could aid in the delivery of healthy offspring for parents who have thalassemia or are hemoglobin gene carriers.', ''),
(82, 'Urticaria', 'Urticaria is a skin rash that presents as an itchy red rash or lumps called weals. The symptoms of urticaria include swollen, reddish patches with distinct borders and itchy skin. Depending on how long it lasts, it might be classified as acute or chronic. While chronic urticaria may last longer than 6 weeks, acute urticaria typically lasts for 6 weeks. Chronic urticaria commonly recurs over the course of weeks and months. Acute urticaria is most frequently brought on by allergic reactions to food, medication, cosmetics, or soap,as well as infections, insect bites or stings, environmental pollution, latex, extremely high or low temperatures, stress, and exercise. Chronic urticaria has several causes, many of which are challenging to determine. Chronic urticaria may occasionally be related to immune system disorders or illnesses like hepatitis or cancer. Avoiding exposure to any known causes, triggers, or allergies will help prevent urticaria. There is no specific treatment for urticaria because the symptoms often go away after a few days in the majority of instances. immune system-compromising disorders or to illnesses like cancer or hepatitis.', ''),
(83, 'Vitiligo', 'Vitiligo is an autoimmune disease. It creates patches and spots of discolored skin at specific places on the body. Lack of melanin (a substance that gives the skin color) is the cause of vitiligo. While vitiligo can affect any area of skin, it most frequently affects hands, the face, neck, and other exposed body parts, as well as skin crevasses. Skin cells called melanocytes are responsible for producing melanin, the substance that gives pigmentation or color to skin. When melanocytes in the body are destroyed by the immune system, the condition results. Complications of vitiligo include skin sensitivity, eye abnormality, emotional challenges like anxiety, and a predisposition to autoimmune conditions like hypothyroidism. Depending on how serious the illness is, different treatments are used. It typically includes anti-autoimmune drugs, skin-lightening lotions applied topically, or surgeries like skin grafting and depigmentation.', ''),
(84, 'Xerostomia', 'Xerostomia is also known as a \"dry mouth disorder\". When a person has xerostomia, their salivary glands are unable to produce enough saliva to keep their mouths moist. Saliva works to stop tooth decay by neutralizing bacterial acids that cause decay. Additionally, saliva improves taste and facilitates meal chewing and swallowing. Reduced salivary secretion can cause anything from slight pain to problems with general health and the condition of your teeth, gums, and oral tissues in general. It typically results as a negative side effect of radiation therapy used in the treatment of cancer, as a symptom of some medical illnesses, or as a side effect of some drugs. Rarely, the salivary gland itself may be the root of the problem. The approach to treatment is created by determining the contributing factors and causes of xerostomia.', ''),
(85, 'Yellow fever', 'Yellow fever is a viral disease often seen in tropical and subtropical regions of South America and Africa that is spread by mosquitoes. The most frequent symptoms are fever, muscle discomfort with a noticeable backache, headache, lack of appetite, and nausea or vomiting, though many people do not have any of these. The Aedes mosquito is the main vector for viral transmission. It has a 3-6 day incubation period, which indicates that it takes 3–6 days after infection for symptoms to start to manifest. A safe and economical vaccine that is incredibly successful at preventing yellow fever is available. The yellow fever vaccination only needs to be administered once to provide lifelong immunity and protection from the disease. There is no need for a booster dose of the vaccine.', 'Y'),
(86, 'Zika virus disease', 'The Zika virus is a virus that is spread by mosquitoes. The Zika forest in Uganda is the place where the virus was initially discovered in 1947, hence its name. The Aedes aegypti mosquito, which also spreads chikungunya, dengue, and yellow fever, is the main vector for the virus\'s transmission to humans. Pregnant women who contract the Zika virus have a higher risk of miscarriage. Microcephaly, a potentially deadly brain disorder, is one of the significant birth defects that are made more likely by Zika virus infection during pregnancy. Symptoms of the Zika virus commonly include mild fever, rashes, joint pain in the hands or feet, conjunctivitis, muscle pain, fatigue, and abdominal pain. For the Zika virus, there is neither a vaccine nor a specific therapy. Precautionary measures can be achieved by installing mesh on the windows, sleeping under mosquito nets, wearing long sleeves, and applying insect repellents. Pregnant women should take special safety precautions to prevent issues like birth deformities.', ''),
(87, 'Bulimia nervosa', 'A potentially fatal eating disorder is bulimia nervosa. This condition causes binge eating. Patients take severe action to prevent weight gain. This results in throwing up (purging). However, it can also refer to extreme fasting or exercise. Although there is no known etiology for bulimia, familial history, psychological stressors, and social factors are likely to play a role in its causes. Regardless of their body weight, people with bulimia nervosa typically have low self-esteem regarding their bodies. It is more prevalent in women and teenagers and can affect anyone who is underweight, normal weight, or overweight. Physical and emotional health are both negatively impacted by bulimia. Every organ system in the body could potentially be disturbed by the difficulties. A multifaceted strategy is typically used to treat this condition, including medication, family therapy, psychotherapy, and nutritional counseling.', ''),
(88, 'Conjunctivitis', 'Infection of the conjunctiva is known as conjunctivitis. The conjunctiva is a clear membrane that lines your eyelid and protects the white part of your eyeball. The inflammation of the conjunctiva causes blood vessel enlargement, which becomes more noticeable as it gets irritated. The white part of the eye becomes reddish or pink as a result of conjunctivitis, giving pink eye its name. Allergies or a bacterial or viral infection can be the cause of conjunctivitis. Conjunctivitis can be quite contagious, as it can be spread through contact with eye secretions from an infected person. Redness, itchiness, and teary eyes are symptoms. Additionally, it may cause crusting or discharge around the eyes. An ophthalmologist will typically conduct a physical examination to confirm the diagnosis, and the course of treatment will depend on the underlying infectious factor. By keeping your hands clean and avoiding exchanging personal items like eyewear, eyedrops, and makeup with infected people, one can prevent conjunctivitis.', 'Y'),
(89, 'Diphtheria', 'Diphtheria is a dangerous bacterial infection that typically impacts the nose and throat mucous membranes. It is caused by the bacteria Corynebacterium diphtheriae. It can spread through droplets during breathing, coughing, speaking, and even laughing. The disease is frequently accompanied by a sore throat, fever, fatigue, nasal discharge, and the development of a membrane on the throat known as a pseudomembrane. Corynebacterium diphtheriae generates toxins that are harmful for the lungs, heart, kidneys, and nervous system. The prevention of diphtheria is done by providing a vaccine. The diphtheria vaccine is typically given in combination with the tetanus and whooping cough vaccines (pertussis). The diphtheria, tetanus, and pertussis vaccination is a three-in-one vaccine. For children, the most recent iteration of this vaccine is known as the DTaP vaccine, while for teenagers and adults, it is known as the Tdap vaccine. These vaccines are generally given in four to five doses at various age levels. The treatment of diphtheria includes the administration of antibiotics and diphtheria antitoxin.', ''),
(90, 'Endometriosis', 'Endometriosis is a disorder in which the endometrium begins to protrude outside of the uterine cavity. Endometrium is the tissue that lines the interior of the uterus, or womb. This endometrial tissue can develop in the pelvic region as well as the ovaries and fallopian tubes of women. Heavy menstrual flow, pelvic pain, and painful urination are common signs of endometriosis. Endometriosis risk factors include early menstruation, having an affected close family member, or being childless. Women between the ages of 25 and 40 are typically affected. Endometriosis-affected women are more likely to experience infertility or have trouble becoming pregnant. The standard diagnosis and treatment of endometriosis are done by laparoscopy or abdominal ultrasonography. Medications such as oral contraceptives, GnRH analogues, and injections to decrease ovarian activity are frequently used as the first line of treatment. In order to address this ailment in its later stages, surgery is frequently the last option.', 'Y'),
(91, 'Fistula', 'An abnormal connection between two organs or cavities in the body is known as a fistula. It can happen everywhere on the body. Anus and rectum infections are the most common because of their susceptibility to infection. Symptoms of a fistula include pain, diarrhea, constipation, fever, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, and exhaustion. An infection that develops in the anal gland is what leads to the majority of anal fistulas. The infection causes an abscess, which either drains naturally or is surgically removed through the skin adjacent to the anus. Depending on the type, nature, and location of a fistula, it can be characterized. Fistulas are typically difficult to manage, although they can be avoided and managed. The severity of the issue will determine how to treat fistulas. Surgery can be required to treat the fistula if it doesn\'t heal with drugs and antibiotics.', ''),
(92, 'Glaucoma', 'Glaucoma is characterized by progressive optic nerve damage. For clear vision, the optic nerve, which transmits visual data from the eye to the brain, is essential. Glaucoma is caused by a relative rise in intraocular pressure (pressure inside the eyes), which can cause irreversible vision loss. High pressure in your eye is frequently associated with damage to the optic nerve. Although glaucoma can affect anyone at any age, it is more prevalent in people over 60. The likelihood of developing glaucoma can be increased by a number of risk factors, such as advanced age, glaucoma in the family, and a history of eye injury. Poor blood supply to the optic nerve and diseases like high blood pressure and diabetes are other factors. Treatment of glaucoma includes eye drops, medication, and surgery.', ''),
(93, 'Hirsutism', 'Hirsutism is a result of excess male hormones, called androgens. Increased amounts of androgens (male sex hormones like testosterone), which are generated by women, are the root cause of this illness. Women of all ages can exhibit hirsutism, or excessive hair growth, which is a frequent clinical disease. The sides of the face, upper lip, chin, upper back, shoulders, sternum, and upper abdomen are the areas of the body where hirsute women typically exhibit higher hair development. All women are recommended to follow a healthy diet and exercise regimen before beginning therapy. Weight loss therapy is advised for obese women since obesity has been linked to higher free testosterone levels, which can worsen hirsutism. Treatment for hirsutism necessitates a thorough clinical assessment and investigation.', ''),
(94, 'Insomnia', 'Insomnia is a common sleep issue. It can make it difficult to get asleep, keep asleep, or lead you to wake up too early and have trouble falling back asleep. When you wake up, you may still feel worn out. Low performance, daily sleepiness, and weariness are some of the immediate effects of insomnia. Long-term implications include poor immunity, indigestion, forgetfulness, an increased risk of heart disease, anxiety, depression, vision difficulties, and even early death. It\'s not always clear what causes insomnia, but stress and anxiety are frequently linked to it. a bad sleeping environment, such as an uncomfortable bed or a noisy, hot, or cold bedroom. lifestyle elements, such as shift work, jet lag, or consuming alcohol or caffeine before bed.', 'Y'),
(95, 'Japanese encephalitis', 'Japanese encephalitis is a viral disease transmitted by mosquito bites. It is most prevalent in rural areas of Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, and the Far East. When mosquitoes attack infected animals, they spread the virus, which is present in pigs and birds. It primarily affects children between the ages of 10 to 15 and occasionally adults. Most incidents are mild. Rarely, it results in severe brain enlargement along with an abrupt headache, a high fever, and confusion. Supportive care is part of the healing process. Wearing long sleeves and long pants, using insect repellents to avoid mosquito bites, and getting the JE vaccine are all common methods of prevention, especially for people who live in or frequently visit endemic areas.', ''),
(96, 'Keratitis', 'In keratitis, cornea becomes inflamed. The cornea, the transparent outer layer of the eye that focuses light. Keratitis can range in intensity from mild to severe, and it can also be accompanied with inflammation in other eye regions. It could potentially affect both eyes (bilateral) or just one (unilateral).Infectious or non-infectious factors can induce keratitis. Microbes include bacteria, fungus, viruses, and parasites are the principal cause behind infectious Keratitis. Local factors that irritate the eye or other systemic eye illnesses are the main causes of noninfectious keratitis. Keratitis usually reacts rapidly and is not difficult to cure. However, if the infection penetrates deeper than the corneal surface, it could leave scars that impede your vision or even result in blindness. Hence, effective and timely management is crucial.', ''),
(97, 'Leprosy', 'Leprosy is a bacterial caused infection.  Mycobacterial leprae causes leprosy. It has a peculiar preference for the skin. Nerves near the skin\'s surface, eyes, earlobes, hands, feet, mucous membranes of the upper respiratory tract, and testicles, are the areas susceptible to leprosy. Leprosy is known to progress gradually and might take anywhere between six months and 40 years before any symptoms appear. Numbness and weakness in the hands and feet, as well as light-colored or red skin areas with diminished sensation, are symptoms. Leprosy can be cured by six to twelve months of multidrug therapy. Leprosy is somtimes contagious and not easily spread. It is not entirely clear how the transmission works. M. Leprae is most likely spread through prolonged, close contact, and repeated exposure to untreated patients via droplets from the mouth and nose. Early intervention prevents impairment.', ''),
(98, 'Myocarditis', 'Myocarditis is a disease in which the heart muscle\'s myocardium becomes inflamed. It is an uncommon form of cardiovascular illness that causes the heart to expand, scar tissues to form, and heart muscle cells to deteriorate. These elements put more strain on the heart as it pumps blood and oxygen throughout the body. People frequently associate heart disease with being older. However, regardless of age, anyone can get myocarditis. Young adults are part of the high-risk group. This condition can be brought on by a wide range of potential causes, including viruses, bacteria, fungus, parasites, autoimmune reactions, and specific drugs. Chest pain, an irregular or rapid heartbeat, breathing problems, fluid buildup with swelling in the lower limbs, fever, exhaustion, and others are some of the usual symptoms of myocarditis. Medication to control the heartbeat and enhance heart function may be part of the treatment. Rare but serious situations could necessitate the use of a device to support cardiac function.', ''),
(99, 'Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS)', 'Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), a hormonal condition that prevents the formation and release of eggs. An excessive number of androgens, or male sex hormones, are produced by the ovaries in PCOS. The polycystic ovarian syndrome is named because some of these eggs grow into cysts, which are the little sacs filled with fluids. Although the exact cause of polycystic ovary syndrome is unknown, it may be a result of both hereditary and environmental factors. Menstrual irregularities, excessive hair growth, acne, and obesity are among the symptoms. PCOS can also increase the risk hypertension, high cholesterol, diabetes, heart diseases, and endometrial cancer. PCOS symptoms can be controlled with the right medical advice. Menstrual cycle control medications can aid in ovulation, slow hair development, and help with other PCOS symptoms.', ''),
(100, 'Rubella', 'The rubella is a viral infection. Rubella is also known as german measles. Most people may only experience minor symptoms from this virus. However, if a mother has the infection while she is pregnant, it can seriously affect the unborn child. Symptoms start to show typically, 2 to 3 weeks after virus exposure. Rash, fever, nausea, and conjunctivitis are among the symptoms. The majority of the time, rashes begin on the face and neck before spreading to other parts of the body. They may last one to three days. The most contagious time is often 1 to 5 days after the rash first appears. Blood tests can be used to diagnose rubella by looking for certain antibodies, such as IgM for a fresh infection and IgG for a previous infection or vaccination. Measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine injection should be timed to avoid rubella. It is a secure and reliable method of preventing rubella in you and your loved ones. Rubella does not have a specific treatment. However, symptomatic treatment such as a healthy diet, enough hydration intake, rest, and vitamin A supplements can aid in symptom relief.', ''),
(101, 'Syphilis', 'Treponema pallidum is the bacterium that causes Syphilis. It is the sexually transmitted illness (STD). Three stages of syphilis symptoms can be distinguished. A person with primary syphilis experiences symptoms 10 days to three months after being exposed to the infection. The first symptom is a tiny, painless chancre that can appear on the mouth, rectum, or genitalia. The symptoms disappears with secondary syphilis, but the rash spreads from the trunk to the entire body. Tertiary syphilis, which starts after years of an initial infection, is the final stage. Syphilis can lead to heart disease, blindness, paralysis, and numbness, among other consequences. Safe sex, staying away from multiple partners, and promoting sex education can all help prevent syphilis. Penicillin G is a common antibiotic used to treat syphilis. Penicillin or the use of other antibiotics like doxycycline, tetracycline, or ceftriaxone is advised in situations of syphilis.', 'Y'),
(102, 'Thrombocytopenia', 'Thrombocytopenia occurs when your body produces less platelets than usual. Blood cells called platelets helps in blood clotting by clumping together and sealing the location of the damage to stop bleeding. Autoimmune illnesses such immune thrombocytopenia (ITP), lupus, and rheumatoid arthritis are the leading cause of thrombocytopenia. Bone marrow can be harmed by cancers like leukaemia or lymphoma, which can kill blood stem cells and ultimately produces less platelets. Blood in the urine or faeces, acute exhaustion, and continuous bleeding from a wound site are all symptoms of thrombocytopenia. Medical diseases that produce increased platelet oxidation, decreased platelet production, increased platelet entrapment, or blood dilution are some of the other causes of thrombocytopenia. Depending on how severe the problem is, thrombocytopenia requires different treatments. Mild cases of low platelet count typically go untreated and just need precaution. Patients are typically given corticosteroids, other drugs, or platelet transfusions in the event of severe symptoms. Spleenectomy surgery is the last option in the last stage of thrombocytopenia.', ''),
(103, 'Urinary tract infections', 'Any infection in the urinary tract is referred to as a urinary tract infection (UTI). The kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra are components of the urinary system. Most infections affect the bladder and urethra, which are parts of the lower urinary system. Women are more prone to urinary tract infections. Pelvic pain, an increase in the urge to urinate, pain when urinating, Burning while urinating, and blood in the urine can all be symptoms of a bladder infection. Back discomfort, nausea, vomiting, and fever are all potential symptoms of a kidney infection. UTIs are brought on by bacteria. However, antibiotics might have negative side effects at any time you take them. Antibiotics are frequently used as a therapy.', ''),
(104, 'Varicose veins', 'Varicose veins are abnormal, dilated blood vessels brought on by the blood vessel walls becoming weaker. They could resemble twisted and bloated clusters of blue or purple veins. These take place because standing and walking put more strain on the lower body\'s veins. In most cases, varicose veins are harmless. This condition\'s cause is unknown. Many people have varicose veins, but they have no symptoms, and they only care about them cosmetically. They can occasionally be the source of painful pain and discomfort or a sign of a circulation issue. Compression stockings, physical activity, or surgeries to seal or remove the veins are all part of the treatment to varicose veins. Self-care practises and compression therapy are included in precautionary management. ', ''),
(105, 'Whooping cough', 'The respiratory condition known as whooping cough is caused by the Bordetella pertussis bacteria. It is very contagious and spread through air droplets. It is also known as pertussis, which means \"a strong cough\" in English. Runny nose, a little cough, and fever are common cold-like symptoms at the beginning of the illness. A dry, lingering cough that makes breathing difficult may appear in two weeks. A dangerous symptom known as apnea, which is a halt in breathing, could develop in patients. It can be challenging to distinguish whooping cough from other common respiratory ailments such a cold, the flu, or bronchitis because the signs and symptoms are similar. Diagnosis can be made on the basis of nose and throat culture. All ages should have the whooping cough vaccine. The diphtheria, tetanus, and whooping cough vaccines are administered together as a combination vaccine to prevent whooping cough (pertussis). Medicine like antibiotics can treat whooping cough.', 'Y'),
(106, 'Xerophthalmia', 'The combination of ocular(eye) signs and symptoms known as xerophthalmia is linked to a severe Vitamin A deficiency. Vitamin A is required for many different processes in the eye. A lack of vitamin A can cause a variety of ocular signs and symptoms that damage the conjunctiva, cornea, and retina. Vitamin A performs several vital tasks in the eye. Xerophthalmia is a significant issue in underdeveloped nations and the main global cause of avoidable blindness. Any age can be affected, however children between the ages of 2 and 6 are especially susceptible to this deficiency. Either insufficient ingestion, metabolism, or storage of vitamin A can result in the condition. Vitamin A deficiency in children can also be avoided by immunising against specific infections like measles, which can lead to xerophthalmia.', ''),
(107, 'Zinc deficiency', 'Zinc is a microelement which means it is required in trace amount by the body. Although its requirement is less, nearly 100 enzymes depend on it to perform essential chemical reactions in body. It plays a crucial role in the production of DNA, cell growth, the synthesis of proteins, the repair of damaged tissue, and the maintenance of a strong immune system. Our bodies are unable to produce zinc, thus it must be obtained externally. Zinc\'s recommended daily intake (RDA) ranges from 3 mg for children to 8 mg and 11 mg for women and adults, respectively. It is more prevalent in nursing and pregnant women. Deficiency of zinc can affect our body majorly. Deficiency of zinc is low levels of zinc (less than 0.66 to 1.10 mcg/ml) in the body are referred to as zinc deficiency. Zinc deficiency can be acquired or congenital that is existing from birth. ', '');
