(109, 'Blood Cancer', 'Blood cancer is also known as leukemia. Leukemia is a disorder in which blood cells proliferate and expand out of control in the lymph nodes and bone marrow. Blood cancer can afflect persons of any age. Certain kinds of blood cancer tend to strike a certain age group more frequently for example, children frequently develop acute lymphocytic leukaemia, a kind of blood cancer. There are numerous varieties of blood cancers, including chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, acute myeloid leukaemia, and acute lymphoblastic leukaemia. Changes (mutations) in the DNA of blood cells are the root cause of all blood malignancies. The blood cells begin to behave strangely as a result of this. These changes are frequently related to factors outside of our control. Many patients with leukaemias that grow slowly don\'t exhibit any symptoms. Symptoms of leukaemias include fatigue, weight loss, recurrent infections, and easily bruising or bleeding. Treatment for leukaemias with a slow growth rate may involve monitoring. Chemotherapy for malignant leukaemias is occasionally combined with radiation therapy and stem cell transplant.', ''),
(110, 'Coronary artery disease', 'The coronary artery disease (CAD) affects coronary arteries, which carry blood to your heart. One or more of your coronary arteries get blocked or progressively narrow with CAD. The blood supply to the heart muscle is subsequently restricted or blocked over time as a result. This can show itself as chest pain (angina), a heart attack (due to an abrupt total blockage of a coronary artery), a progressive progression to heart failure, or even sudden death due to a rhythm disruption that poses a serious risk to life. Plaque accumulation in the walls of the arteries supplying blood to the heart is what causes coronary artery disease (called coronary arteries). Deposits of cholesterol make form plaque. Over time, plaque formation causes the interior of the arteries to narrow. Atherosclerosis is the name of this process. The symptoms of coronary heart disease (CHD) can be managed with treatment, and the likelihood of developing new issues is decreased. Effective management of CHD can be achieved through a combination of medication, lifestyle modifications, and, occasionally, surgery. ', ''),
(111, 'Dementia', 'A set of symptoms that substantially impair memory, reasoning, social skills, and when they significantly interfere with day-to-day functioning are referred to be dementia. Although there isn\'t one particular illness that causes dementia, many illnesses can. Memory loss is a common symptom of dementia. There are various possible causes of dementia. Poor blood flow, aberrant protein buildup, and degenerative changes in the brain are just a few of them. Simple symptoms like forgetting crucial dates or events might develop into more severe ones like forgetting to put on clothing or eat on time as the condition worsens. Dementia is a progressive mental condition and can worsen with time. Symptoms of dimentia can be suppressed by medications but one can\'t treat it completely.', 'Y'),
(112, 'Eczema', 'Eczema is a widespread chronic skin illness characterised by skin areas that are dry, extremely itchy, and irritated. Although there are other varieties of eczema, the word \"eczema\" typically refers to the condition known as \"atopic dermatitis,\" which is the most common variety. An interaction between environmental and genetic disturbance leads to atopic dermatitis. In most cases eczema symptoms are mild. The most common symptoms of eczema include dry, scaly skin, skin flushing, itching, open, crusted, or weeping sores. Eczema can last a lifetime, and patients frequently have long stretches of symptom-free remission followed by brief but severe flare-ups. However, by maintaining healthy, moisturised skin, symptoms can be avoided and controlled at home with care and solutions. Corticosteroid creams can be used as a treatment for eczema as they\'re good ailment to allergies. ', 'Y'),
(113, 'Fungal skin infections', 'Fungus is the cause of fungal skin infections. Fungal skin infections primarily affect the moist body parts and skin folds, such as the vaginal region, armpits, under the breasts, and groyne region. Yeast and dermatophytes(a type of fungi that causes superficial infections of the skin, hair, and nails) are the main cause behind these diseases. The infection may lead to the rash when your skin comes into contact with a dangerous fungus. For instance, the fungus could contact your foot if you borrowed a pair of shoes from someone who had athlete\'s foot and infect you. Direct contact between people or animals and people often results in fungal skin infection. The infection may lead to the rash when skin comes into contact with a dangerous fungus. For instance, the fungus could contact your foot if you borrowed a pair of shoes from someone who had athlete\'s foot and infect you. ', ''),
(114, 'Gastroenteritis', 'Intestinal inflammation (irritation) is referred to as gastroenteritis. Gastroenteritis can also affect your colon and small intestine. Although viruses are the most common cause, it can also be brought on by bacteria, toxins, parasites, certain chemicals, and drugs. Gastroenteritis typically causes abdominal discomfort, stomach pain, vomiting, and watery diarrhoea. It is easily transmitted from one infected individual to another through close contact or by touching contaminated surfaces since it is contagious. Consumption of tainted foods and drinks can lead to the gastroenteritis virus. Basic hand hygiene practices, rapid disinfection of contaminated surfaces, and avoiding contaminated food and water can prevent the majority of instances of gastroenteritis. Most gastroenteritis cases can be managed at home with a regular diet of clear soups, coconut water, clean boiled water, oral rehydration solution (ORS), and fresh fruit juices.', 'Y'),
(115, 'Hypercalcemia', 'Hypercalcemia refers to an elevated blood calcium level. Blood calcium levels that are too high can affect your heart and brain function as well as damage your bones and cause kidney stones. Hyperactive parathyroid glands cause hypercalcemia. Normal calcium level in blood is 8.8 mg/dL-10.8 mg/dL. Hypercalcemia is classified into mild hypercalcemia (10.5 to 11.9 mg/dL), moderate hypercalcemia (12.0 to 13.9 mg/dL), and hypercalcemic crisis (14.0 to 16.0 mg/dL). Most occurrences of hypercalcemia are caused by malignancy and primary hyperparathyroidism. Hypercalcemia can cause minor to severe signs and symptoms. Hypercalcemia can lead to kidney stones, brittle bones, and problems related to the heart and brain. Treatment may include medicines or surgical removal of an parathyroid gland.', ''),
(116, 'Indigestion', 'Indigestion is also referred to as dyspepsia. It is a feeling of pain or discomfort in the upper abdomen that is accompanied by a sense of fullness, bloating, and flatulence. Sedentary lifestyle, dietary habits, particular drugs, and specific gastrointestinal disorders including GERD are a few of the frequent reasons of indigestion. In most situations, dyspepsia may be managed with minor dietary and lifestyle adjustments, moderate alcohol and fizzy beverage consumption, and regular physical activity. The use of over-the-counter (OTC) drugs such antacids is advised to treat dyspepsia if lifestyle changes are ineffective. To treat the underlying cause of indigestion, prescription medications such as prokinetics and antibiotics may also be suggested. Antacid use can reduce indigestion symptoms. Losing weight, eating smaller, more frequent meals, chewing food completely, and avoiding triggers like fatty foods and fizzy beverages can prevent indigestion.', 'Y'),
(117, 'Kidney failure', 'Kidney failure is a disorder in whic one or both kidneys stop working. Kidney failure can be acute or chronic. Acute kidney damage, or AKI, can occur suddenly in some people and cause temporary renal failure. In the chronic kidney disease or CKD patients, this illness might develop gradually and get worse over time. Vomiting, stomachache, decreased urine production, dry or itchy skin, confusion, hallucination, and a metallic taste to food are just a few of the many symptoms that kidney failure patients experience. Although kidney failure can be a serious medical issue, if a patient receives assistance in a timely manner, it can be addressed. Dialysis and appropriate medicine to kidney failure\'s causes and symptoms form the cornerstone of care. A failing kidney\'s last resort is typically a kidney transplant. A patient with renal failure would need ongoing care from their doctor, including follow-up visits.', ''),
(118, 'Kidney cancer', 'Cancer that starts in the kidneys is known as kidney cancer. Normally, kidneys are two bean-shaped organs, each around the size of your fist. One kidney is situated on either side of the spine, and they are situated behind your abdominal organs. Renal cell carcinoma is the most prevalent form of kidney cancer in adults. A kidney cancer type known as Wilms\' tumour is more common in young children. Smoking is the main risk factor for kidney cancer. Additional contributing factors include having certain hereditary diseases, being exposed to certain chemicals, high blood pressure, diabetes, obesity, kidney stones, long-term dialysis, and diabetes. Most people don\'t exhibit any early-stage cancer symptoms or indicators. Usually, an accidental finding during an abdominal imaging exam will reveal kidney cancer. A person may experience symptoms including blood in the urine, lower back pain, a lump or swelling in the abdomen or around the kidneys, and untimely weight loss as the tumour grows. Surgery, targeted therapy, immunotherapy, or a combination of these treatments are typically used to treat kidney cancer. Chemotherapy and radiation therapy are occasionally applied.', 'Y'),
(119, 'Lung Cancer', 'Lung cancer is caused by unchecked cell division in your lungs. Lung cells naturally divide and create additional copies of themselves. Occasionally they experience mutations that lead them to continue to divide without stoppingw. The uncontrolled division of damaged cells results in tissue tumours, which eventually prevent lung from functioning properly. Lung cancer\'s exact cause is still a mystery.  Lung cancer can be brought on by smoking, passive smoking, exposure to specific chemicals, and family history. Smoking, however, is the main contributor to this condition, and long-term smoking has been linked to an increased risk of lung cancer. It has been demonstrated that quitting smoking dramatically lowers a person\'s risk of lung diseases. Lung cancer can be of two types: non-small cell lung cancer and small cell lung cancer. Symptoms of lung cancer include general lung dysfuntion, cough with blood, chest pain, wheezing, and weight loss. Surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, targeted medication therapy, and immunotherapy are few examples of possible treatments.', 'Y'),
(120, 'Low immunity', 'People with low or weak immune system are at higher risk of getting infections. The immune system plays a crucial role in defending your body against pathogens, toxic chemicals, and cell alterations that could make you ill. It is composed of several cells, organs, and proteins. The body\'s natural immune system serves as first line of defence against any diseases occuring from outside sources. The chance of being severely harmed by even the most basic illnesses increases if for some reason the body\'s immune systems is compromised. Smoking, alcohol consumption, and poor  nutrition can all damage the immune system. HIV infection, which causes AIDS, is an acquired viral infection that impairs the immune system and kills crucial white blood cells. Individuals with HIV/AIDS develop severe infections that the majority of people can fend off. Other causes of immunodeficiency can be hereditary or acquired infections. Low immunity makes a person more susceptible to frequent infections that can be fatal. Following a healthy lifestyle that includes regular exercise, a well-balanced diet, less stress, etc. will help you build a stronger immune system and stay healthy.', ''),
(121, 'Measles', 'Measles is a mild respiratory viral disease.  Symptom include a pathognomonic enanthema (Koplik or white spots), maculopapular rash precede a prodrome of fever (up to 105°F), malaise, cough, coryza, and conjunctivitis. In most cases, the rash develops 14 days after exposure. Blindness, severe respiratory infections like pneumonia, and ear infections are some of the measles side effects. Measles is very contagious and can spread to vulnerable individuals through even the slightest contact with an active case. It spreads through airdroplets in which the virus first attacks the respiratory tract and then spreads throughout the body. Thus, every precaution should be taken to prevent its spread, especially among people with reduced immune systems, such as newborns, children, pregnant women, or patients with immunodeficiency. The MMR vaccine provides protection against measles, mumps, and rubella. It should be administered time to time. The measles has no specific treatment. Although, symptomatic treatment such as healthy eating, drinking enough water, getting enough rest, and taking vitamin A supplements can help to reduce symptoms.', 'Y'),
(122, 'Melanoma', 'Melanoma is the most severe type of skin cancer. Malignant cancer cells can develop in melanoma. Melonocytes are cells that colour the skin and get affected in melanoma. There are various cancers that develop in the skin. Melanoma can appear anywhere on the skin. Fair skin, light hair, light-colored eyes, a history of extensive sun exposure, close relatives who have developed melanoma, and irregular, numerous, large-sized moles are people with risk of melanoma. A new, peculiar growth or a change in an existing mole could be symptoms of melanoma. Melanoma must be diagnosed and treated as soon as possible. Skin changes or odd areas should be reported immediately to a doctor. A biopsy, in which a portion of skin containing the pigmented tumour is excised for laboratory examination, is typically used to make the diagnosis. Surgery, radiation, medicine, and in rare situations chemotherapy are all possible forms of treatment. ', ''),
(123, 'Meningitis', 'Meninges are the coverings of brain and spinal cord. The inflammation of meninges is called meningitis. Meningitis is also known as brain fever, Meningoencephalitis or Cerebromeningitis. Bacteria, viruses, fungi, parasites infections or non-infectious conditions like cancer, systemic lupus erythematosus, side effect of specific drugs, head trauma, and brain surgery can lead in meningitis. The main risk factors for meningitis include inadequate immunisation, old age, chronic health issues, poor sanitation, and residing in high endemic areas. Symptoms of meningitis include genral fever, severe headache, neck stiffness, nausea, vomiting and light sensitivity. Patient may feel confusion, lack of appetite, lethargy and trouble waking up. Meningitis is a medical emergency that needs to be treated right away. Antibiotics and steroids are used to treat bacterial meningitis, whereas supportive care is typically used to treat viral meningitis. To prevent serious complications like hearing loss, memory issues, speech issues, and sepsis, prompt management is essential.', 'Y'),
(124, 'Menopause', 'Menopause means stoppage of menstruation. It occurs at the age of 40-55. It is physiological process. Menopause is seen as a normal aspect of ageing and is neither a sickness nor a pathology. While some women may go through the menopause transition with no symptoms at all and no problems, others may encounter a variety of symptoms such as difficulty sleeping, hot flashes, night sweats, irritability, mood swings, hair loss, joint pain, and weight gain. Menopause is indicated by no mentstruation by the passage of one year. Hot flushes and vaginal dryness are typical symptoms. These symptoms together can result in anxiety or depression. Treatments for menopause concentrate on the symptomatic relief. Topical lubricants or oestrogen are used to eliminate vaginal dryness. The intensity and frequency of hot flushes can be lessened with medication. Oral hormone therapy may be employed in unique situations.', 'Y'),
(125, 'Monkeypox', 'Monkeypox is a virus caused disease. It is zoonotic and hence can be transfered from rodents like rats, mice, and squirrels, or by eating raw meat of infected animals. Close contact with lesions, bodily fluids, respiratory droplets, and contaminated items like bedding can all spread monkeypox from one person to another. Monkeypox mostly affects people living in tropical rainforest regions of central and west Africa and occasionally transported to other locations. High fever, headache, muscular aches, backaches, enlarged glands, chills, tiredness, and joint discomfort are among the early signs of monkeypox. Typically, monkeypox is a minor, self-healing condition. There isn\'t an effective cure for this virus as of now. The key component of the treatment plan is supportive care, which reduces the patient\'s symptoms. Mild disease patients typically heal without the need for medical attention. Others might need support of antiviral medications to get heal.', ''),
(126, 'Mumps', 'One or more painful canker sores on inner lips, gums, tongue, roof of the mouth or throat that may interfere with eatingis a sign of mouth ulcer. Canker sores and sores brought on by hand, foot, and mouth diseases are two examples of mouth ulcer types. Mouth ulcers are rarely communicable and often go away on their own in 1 to 2 weeks. Mouth ulcers can affect anyone. Although there is no known cause for these ulcers, several things can trigger them, including mental stress, lack of sleep, certain nutritional deficiencies, trauma from harsh brushing, accidental bites, allergies, and infections. The majority of mouth ulcers heal on their own. Topical medications may be administered to lessen discomfort and lower the possibility of complications. Antiseptic gels, steroid ointments, or pharmaceutical mouth rinses are frequently used to treat mouth ulcers. ', 'Y'),
(127, 'Mucormycosis', 'Mucormycosis is a disease caused by fungi. A class of moulds known as mucormycetes are the source of the deadly and rare fungal infection. These moulds are present everywhere in the environment. Those with low immunity, health issues, or those who take medications that impair the body\'s capacity to fight disease are more likely to develop mucormycosis. One-sided facial swelling, headaches, congestion in the nose or sinuses, rapidly worsening black lesions on the roof of the mouth, and fever are all signs of mucormycosis. Treatment of mucormycosis include Amphotericin B and other antifungal medications. This disease can be prevented by effective management of underlying or causing medical disorders. In severe cases, surgical excision of infected tissue is necessary for treatment.', ''),
(128, 'Multiple myelosis', 'Multiple myeloma is a cancer that develops in plasma cell. Plasma cells are type of B lymphocytes. Healthy plasma cells produce antibodies that destroys antigens, assisting body\'s immune system in fighting illnesses. Cancerous plasma cells build up in the bone marrow and crowd out healthy blood cells in multiple myeloma. Myeloma cells keep trying to create antibodies, but they instead produce aberrant antibodies that the body cannot utilise. Aberrant antibodies accumulate in the body and lead to issues including kidney damage. Bone damage brought on by cancer cells raises the possibility of bone fractures. The intensity of multiple myeloma symptoms varies depending on the cancer stage and the individual. Weight loss, bone pain, nausea, recurrent infections, exhaustion, confusion, and loss of appetite are a few of the symptoms that are frequently experienced. Treatments of multiple myeloma include medication, chemotherapy, corticosteroids, radiation or a stem-cell transplant.', ''),
(129, 'Nail infection', 'Nail infection are coomon in elderly people. It is usually due to fungal infection. Many kinds of fungi that are present in the environment are what cause fungus-related nail diseases. These germs can enter your nail through tiny holes in the skin around it or in your nail, inflicting an infection. The majority of fungus nail infections are not dangerous. Nonetheless, some people could feel pain or worry about how their nails look. Nails that have been infected by fungi may become thick, brittle, or cracked. Another possibility is for the nail to detach from the nail bed. The majority of fungus nail infections are not dangerous. Nonetheless, some people could feel pain or worry about how their nails look. Nails that have been infected by fungi may become thick, brittle, or cracked. Antibacterial or antifungal medications are used orally and topically as treatment. In severe circumstances, surgery can be necessary.', ''),
(130, 'Nausea', 'Nausea is the feeling of being sick. Experts consider this more as a symptom rather than disease. Vomiting is the act of forcing stomach contents up through the mouth, either voluntarily or involuntarily. Food poisoning, peptic ulcers, motion sickness, pregnancy, and brain abnormalities are just a few of the illnesses that can induce nausea, which can also be acute or persistent, physical or psychological. In the first trimester of pregnancy, it happens a lot. It can also be thought of as a side effect of some medicines or as a result of radiation and chemotherapy. Women are observed to experience nausea three times more frequently than men. An occasional or moderate case of nausea and vomiting can be safely treated at home without seeking medical help. However, medical attention is required if the nausea is chronic in character or if numerous episodes of nausea and vomiting happen quickly.', ''),
(131, 'Neck pain', 'Neck pain is very unpleasant pain at cervical region of the body. It limits mobility and can make daily activities difficult. Neck pain results from the severe strain this places on the neck. Neck pain appears due to disregard sitting in the proper posture or due to the sedentary lifestyle, which includes long hours spent working on laptops and reading through social media. Symptoms of the neck pain includes muscle spasm, tightness, headache and severe pain in mobility. Neck pain may be relieved by using an ice pack and a heat pack alternately for 30 minutes each time, light stretching, and massage. Good posture and gentle exercise may also help to prevent it. Ibuprofen and paracetamol, two common painkillers, may also be helpful.', ''),
(132, 'Obesity', 'Obesity refers to having too much body fat. When a person\'s body mass index is 25 or higher, they are considered obese. Obesity is more than simply a cosmetic issue. It is a medical condition that raises the chance of various illnesses and conditions, including heart disease, diabetes, high blood pressure, and some malignancies. Obesity can have many causes. Its cause has variety of elements, including genetics, environment, physical inactivity, food preferences, lifestyle decisions, specific medical problems, and the use of specific drugs. Taking in more calories than you burn via exercise and everyday activities is a common cause of obesity. The chance of developing major health issues rises as a result of high body fat. The objective of obesity therapy is to reach and maintain a healthier weight. The therapy involves a lifetime commitment to healthy eating choices, greater physical activity, and frequent exercise, however drugs and some operations may be helpful. ', 'Y'),
(133, 'Oral cancer', 'Cancer which can develop in any parts of mouth including lips, gums, tongue, cheeks, roof or floor of the mouth, and the portion of the throat behind the mouth. is called Oral cancer. The term \"oral cancer\" refers to the abnormal development of body cells in any area of the mouth. Symptoms include a sore that doesn\'t heal, a lump or a white or red patch on the inside of the mouth. Oral cancer risk increases with the use of any tobacco product, including cigarettes, cigars, pipes, chewing tobacco, and others. The danger is further increased by heavy consumption of alcohol. Human papillomavirus (HPV) patients also have an increased risk of getting mouth cancer. Oral cancer symptoms include: a lip or mouth sore, a white or reddish patch on the inside of your mouth, loosening of teeth, a lump inside your mouth, mouth pain, ear pain, and difficulty while swallowing and chewing. Treatment of oral cancer includes chemptherapy, surgery and radiation therapy. ', ''),
(134, 'Oral thrush', 'Oral thrush is a fungal infection caused by the fungus Candida albicans. It develops creamy white sores on tongue or inner cheeks. Occasionally, tonsils, gums, and the back of the throat can become infected with oral thrush. The signs of this disease include fever, mouth burning, taste loss, mouth cracking at the corners, pain or trouble swallowing, a sense of food being trapped in the throat, and pain or difficulty swallowing. Babies, those with immunological deficiencies, and adults who take steroid sprays for asthma are all susceptible to oral thrush. The easiest method to avoid it is to practise oral hygiene, take care of senior patient dentures, and visit the dentist frequently. For milder cases, home treatments and application of antifungal mouthwashes and ointments can be used to control the condition. Topical or medicational antifungal drugs are the major part of treatment. ', ''),
(135, 'Osteoarthritis', 'Osteoarthritis is inflammation of joints due to age related degeration in bones. Womens, elderly and obese people are more likely to have osteoarthritis.  The bone alterations of the joints, the breakdown of tendons and ligaments, the breakdown of cartilage (the tissue that cushions the ends of the bones between joints), and varying degrees of inflammation of the joint lining are its defining characteristics. The main signs and symptoms of the condition are joint abnormalities, stiffness, progressive discomfort in the hands, neck, lower back, knees, or hips. Osteoarthritis-related problems such as pain, decreased mobility, drug side effects, and other factors can result in health issues that are unrelated to the disease itself. Medication, physical therapy, and occasionally surgery can assist retain joint mobility and lessen discomfort.', 'Y'),
(136, 'Osteomalacia', 'The osteomalacia disorder causes bones to soften and weaken is osteomalacia. As a result, they are more brittle and susceptible to breaking. The structural integrity of bones is maintained by certain minerals and vitamins like calcium, phosphorous, magnessium and vitamin D. Calcium and phosphorus levels are regulated by vitamin D in the body. An individual gets osteomalacia if there is an imbalance of these minerals, which typically results from a vitamin D deficiency. Symptoms of osteomalacia include bone discomfort, muscular weakness, gait problems, and a higher risk of bone fractures. It occurs in adults. It is known as rickets in children and results in poor mineralization at the bone development plate.Osteomalacia and osteoporosis both conditions can cause bones to fracture. Osteomalacia can be treated by giving the patient enough calcium and vitamin D, both of which are important for strengthening and hardening the bones.', ''),
(137, 'Palpitations', 'Heart palpitations are the experience of having a pounding or racing heart. The throat, chest, or neck experience these pounding or palpitations of heart. Patient\'s heart may seem to be beating too quickly or forcefully in caase of palpitations. A skipped heartbeat or a fluttering heartbeat are some possible symptoms. The symptoms of palpitations also include having a heartbeat that feels like it is beating, skipping beats, or flip-flopping. Palpitations makes you feel uncomfortable, anxious and scared. But, palpitations often aren\'t hazardous and normally go away on their own. People frequently feel palpitations as a result of stress, worry, or overindulging in alcohol, nicotine, or caffeine. Palpitations are a typical symptom for pregnant women. Palpitations occasionally can be result of a significant heart disorder. If you suffer palpitations accompanied with shortness of breath, chest pain, or fainting, you should seek emergency medical assistance. The etiology of palpitations will determine the most suitable course of treatment. Doctor advise breathing exercises, yoga, aromatherapy, and other techniques to help relax the heart.', ''),
(138, 'Pancreatic cancer', 'Pancreatic cancer is cancer that occurs in the cells of the pancreas. Pancreatic cancer begins in the tissues of pancreaswhich is an organ in the abdomen which functions as endocrine and exocrine organ. Tumors developed in pancreas continue to develop as a result of the uncontrolled growth of pancreatic cells and other body parts may potentially become infected by the malignant cnacerous cells. Pancreatic cancer type ductal adenocarcinoma is the most prevalent form of pancreatic cancer. It develops in the cells that lining the ducts that remove digestive enzymes from the pancreas. Early pancreatic cancer frequently has no visible symptoms at all. By the time they start to exhibit symptoms, they have frequently expanded significantly or spread outside the pancreas. Late stage of pancreatic cancer signs and symptoms includes upper abdominal pain, abdominal pain that radiates to your back, tenderness when touching the abdomen, fever, rapid pulse, nausea, vomiting. The treatment of pancreatic cancer are based on the extent of the cancer and may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these.', 'Y'),
(139, 'Pancreatitis', 'Pancreatitis is inflammation of the pancreas. The pancreas is a long, flat gland that sits tucked behind the stomach in the upper abdomen. The pancreas produces enzymes that help digestion and hormones that help regulate the way your body processes sugar (glucose). Early pancreatic cancer frequently has no visible symptoms at all. By the time they start to exhibit symptoms, they have frequently expanded significantly or spread outside the pancreas. Constant stomach pain is the primary sign of acute pancreatitis. It frequently spreads to the lower belly, lower back, chest, and waist. Diabetes, infections, bleeding, and kidney issues can also be caused by it. Diarrhea, vomiting, weight loss, and ongoing upper stomach pain are all signs of chronic pancreatitis.  Pancreatitis may be acute or chronic. The most common causes are alcohol abuse and lumps of gallstones in the gallbladder. Medication and lifestyle changes are the pain management plan. The symptoms can be greatly reduced by abstaining from alcohol and tobacco use, eating small, frequent meals, and consuming foods strong in antioxidants such folate. ', ''),
(140, 'Peptic Ulcer disease', 'The condition known as peptic ulcer disease is occurs when open sores or ulcers develop in the lower oesophagus or stomach or duodenum of the small intestine. Gastric ulcer refers to a peptic ulcer in the stomach. A peptic ulcer that appears in the first section of the small intestine is called a duodenal ulcer (duodenum). The lower portion of your esophagus is where an esophageal ulcer develops. Helicobacter pylori (H pylori) infection of the digestive tract is the most frequent cause of ulcers. Peptic ulcer causes indigestion, burning senstation in stomach and bloating. Peptic ulcer disease (PUD) complications include bleeding, penetration, perforation, and obstruction of the stomach outlet. Diagnosis can be done by endoscopy or CT scan of upper GI tract. Treatment of peptic ulcer can depend upon the origin of the ulcer, the patient\'s age, and general health. Doctor preferably prescribe proton pump inhibitors, antacids, and antibiotics as treatments. ', ''),
(141, 'Period Pain (menstrual cramps)', 'Period pain or menstrual cramps is also known as dysmenorrhea Regular short-term absences from job, school, or college are indicators of it. Dysmenorrhea, as it is known medically, has an effect on a person\'s ability to concentrate, interact with others, and achieve. Dysmenorrhea is of twoo types. Primary dysmenorrhea is menstrual pain without an underlying condition and secondary dysmenorrhea is the type of dysmenorrhea in which menstrual pain associated with some pelvic pathology. Home remedies and alternative therapies like heat therapy, dietary supplements including vitamins B1, B6, E, and omega 3 fatty acids, a low-fat vegetarian diet, and acupressure have shown great relief painful periods. Women with primary dysmenorrhea can start with nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs as treatment. Oral contraceptives may be coupled with NSAIDs if they are insufficient on their own. Depending on the reason, progestin-only treatments or surgery may also be options in cases of secondary dysmenorrhea.', ''),
(142, 'Piles', 'Piles is known as haemorrhoids in medical terms. Piles are swelling that contain enlarging blood vessels in the rectum and anus. Haemorrhoids frequently go unnoticed, and some people aren\'t even aware they have them. Constipation, pregnancy, being overweight or obese, recurrent diarrhea, spending a lot of time on the toilet, and straining to move heavy objects are all risk factors for piles. Hemorrhoids can develop from increased pressure in the lower rectum and anus. Hemorrhoid symptoms include itching or irritation in anal region, pain or discomfort, swelling around anus and bleeding. Hemorrhoids can be treated by home remedies like consuming high fibre foods and soaking the region in warm water. Medical treatment includes the topical application of  hydrocortisone and lidocaine or surgical external hemorrhoid thrombectomy.', ''),
(143, 'Prostate cancer', 'One of the most prevalent cancers is prostate cancer. Cancer that develops in the prostate is known as prostate cancer. In males, the prostate is a little walnut-shaped gland that secretes seminal fluid, which feeds and carries sperm. The prostate gland\'s cells start to multiply abnormally in prostate cancer. It is more likely to affect men over the age of 50. The risk of prostate cancer rises with age. diet, ethnicity, genetic mutations, and family history. Symptoms of prostate cancer trouble urinating or decreased force of stream, blood in the urine or semen, bone pain, unexpected weight loss, and unexplained fevers. Prostate biopsy, a PSA test, and a digital rectal examination are used to make the diagnosis. Cancer staging affects the prognosis and therapy of prostate cancer. The following medical methods can be used to treat prostate cancer cell growth: observation, active surveillance, surgery (radical prostatectomy), radiation therapy, hormone therapy, chemotherapy, immune/vaccine therapy, and others.', 'Y'),
(144, 'Prostatitis', 'Between the penis and bladder is a tiny gland called the prostate. Inflammation (swelling) of the prostate gland is referred to as prostatitis. Any age can develop prostate cancer. Prostatitis can be caused by bacterial infection. Symptoms of prostatitis are burning sensation when urinating, difficulty urinating, such as dribbling or hesitant urination, frequent urination, nocturia, blood in the urine, and pain in the abdomen, groin or lower back. Prostatitis can be acute and chronic bacterial prostatitis. Men with lower UTIs may be more likely to develop bacterial prostatitis. UTIs that recur or are difficult to treat may lead to chronic bacterial prostatitis. Acute or chronic bacterial prostatitis can be cured by antibiotics. Acute disease may require intravenous (IV) antibiotics in the hospital for a short period. The entire course of antibiotic treatment is usually 4 to 6 weeks — or longer in some cases.', ''),
(145, 'Psoriasis', 'Psoriasis is the skin disorder. Skin and nails are the main areas affected in psoriasis. Skin lesions which are elevated red plaques that can be localized or generalized and are typically covered with white or silver scales are common in psoriasis. A lesion may hurt and itch. Joint discomfort is also a side effect of psoriatic arthritis, which occurs in certain people. Inflammation may also develop in the kidneys, lungs, heart, eyes, and heart muscle due to psoriasis. Contributing factors for psoriasis are believed to be autoimmune and genetic predisposition. Psoriasis can be triggered by various factors, including as trauma, throat infections, sunburn, specific drugs, stress, etc. Psoriasis treatment focuses on symptom management. The most common treatments are phototherapy, topical and systemic therapies, or a combination of these. The requirement for treatment is typically permanent and is geared at extended periods of remission.', 'Y'),
(146, 'Pulmonary embolism', 'When a blood clot becomes lodged in a lung artery and prevents blood flow to a portion of the lung, the condition is known as a pulmonary embolism (PE). Most frequently, blood clots begin in the legs, move through the right side of the heart, and enter the lungs. DVT is the medical term for. It is typically observed in older people, and men are more frequently impacted than women.  Chest pain, an irregular heartbeat, a weak pulse, palpitations (racing heart), perspiration, and low blood pressure are among PE\'s most typical symptoms. Risk factors for pulmonary embolism include genetic disorders that enhance the likelihood of blood clot formation, family history, advanced age, obesity, cigarette smoking, and obesity. An anticoagulant drug is the primary therapy for pulmonary embolism. This medication alters the chemical composition of your blood to prevent it from clotting. ', ''),
(147, 'Rheumatoid arthritis', 'Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune and inflammatory condition in which your immune system unintentionally assaults healthy cells of the body, leading to inflammation and painful swelling in the areas of affected. RA primarily targets joints, typically more than one join at a time. Rheumatoid arthritis produces excruciating swelling in the joints of wrists, hands, and knees. Joint pain, swelling, and stiffness are among the symptoms, which are at higher intensity in the morning. Fever and appetite loss follow the patient\'s feeling of exhaustion. Although there is no permanent cure for rheumatoid arthritis, early treatment can improve prognosis. The spread of the disease can be slowed down, its symptoms can be controlled, and joint deformity can be avoided with the aid of drugs and, on occasion, surgery. Living a healthy, active lifestyle, keeping a weight in control, and using self-care techniques to manage symptoms can all help to reduce effects of RA.', 'Y'),
(148, 'Ringworm ', 'Ringworm infection is a common fungal infection that affects skin of the body like scalp, beard, hands, nails, groin, inner thighs, and feet.. The appearance of circular and oblong rashes on the skin that resemble worms gives the illness its name. Ringworm is known to be caused by a number of fungal species, including Trichophyton, Microsporum, and Epidermophyton. It is a contagious disease that can spread from one person to other. Symptoms of ringworm includes itchy skin, ring-shaped rash, redness, scaly and cracked skin, and hair loss. With the appropriate use topical and oral antifungal drugs, that are available as creams, gels, sprays, shampoos, lotions, tablets, and capsules, ringworm can be easily treated. Even in the absence of symptoms, the recommended course of therapy must be followed to completion for a full recovery and to prevent recurrence.', ''),
(149, 'Schizophrenia', 'Schizophrenia is a pchychological disorder. It can drastically impair one\'s capacity for rational thought processing, emotional regulation, and decision-making. Delusions, hallucinations, abnormal behavior, mental processes, speech alterations, and mood changes are a few of the typical symptoms of schizophrenia. The kind and intensity of these symptoms can fluctuate over time. Periods of intermittent symptom exacerbation and remission are possible in schizophrenia. People with schizophrenia frequently experience paranoid ideas or hear voices. Schizophrenia is treated with antipsychotic medication, patient support, and management of the psychotic symptoms. The illness is widely misunderstood, and people who suffer from schizophrenia are frequently subjected to societal stigma. Yet, patients are now able to live better lives at home and near to their loved ones because of more knowledge and better treatment alternatives.', 'Y'),
(150, 'Sciatica', 'Sciatica refers to leg discomfort, achiness, numbness, or tingling. It is caused by pressure or damage to the sciatic nerve. . Older persons are typically affected by this ailment. Men more often have an impact on women. Sciatica is a sign of a vertebral issue. Sciatica most frequently brought on by disc-related conditions such disc herniation or bony overgrowths. Cancer, infections, or blood vessel compression are examples of non-disc causes. Sciatica can cause have a slight tingling, aching, or burning sensation. In rare instances, the agony is so bad that it renders a person immobile. The pain typically only affects one side of leg. Some patients have severe discomfort in one hip or leg or both while some have numbness in other areas A drop foot effect, or difficulty elevating the front half of the foot, can result from severe nerve damage. The lack of bowel and bladder control may be another consequence. Treatment differs according on the condition\'s severity and underlying cause. Many care strategies include conservative measures like maintaining an active lifestyle, using painkillers, getting acupuncture, epidural steroid injections, manipulating the spine, and physical therapy. In severe circumstances, surgery can be necessary.', ''),
(151, 'Sinusitis', 'Inflammation or swelling of the tissue lining of the sinuses is known as sinusitis. There are four pairs of sinuses in the skull. Sinuses are cavities or spaces. They\'re linked by tiny channels. Each sinus in a healthy person is lined with a membrane that secretes mucus. The upper portion of your nose is filled with a thin, watery liquid called muscus that freely drains from your sinuses. This drainage assists in keeping the nose germ-free and clean. Mucus becomes thick and sticky and is unable to move into the nose when sinuses become inflamed by a virus, bacterial infection, allergies, or other irritants. Because of the fluid buildup as a result, pressure, discomfort, and other symptoms are experienced in the sinuses.  Sinusitis can be treated by the application of nasal decongestants, antiallegens and antibiotics medication. In mild sinusitis, patient can do some home remedies like steam inhalation, use of saline nasal drops, properly hydrate the body and use of humidifier. ', 'Y'),
(152, 'Sjogren\'s syndrome', 'Sjogren\'s syndrome is an autoimmune disorder. The two most typical symptoms of Sjogren\'s syndrome are dry eyes and a dry mouth. The syndrome frequently coexists with other immune system diseases like lupus and rheumatoid arthritis. The illness can appear at any age, but it is more frequently identified in women and those who are over 40. Combinations of hereditary and environmental variables cause Sjögren\'s syndrome. Some people are born with particular genes that make them more susceptible to immune system problems. Sjogren\'s syndrome frequently coexists with immune system diseases including lupus and rheumatoid arthritis (an autoimmune condition causing inflammation of joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs). The primary goals of treatment are to reduce the symptoms and consequences brought on by dry mouth, dry eyes, and other symptoms. ', 'Y'),
(153, 'Sore throat', 'Sore throat is an uneasy feeling in throat. It is recognised by throat discomfort, itching, or irritation that is typically brought on by a virus but may also be brought on by bacteria. Moreover, sore throats might be caused by environmental factors such as pollution, smoking, seasonal allergies, or food allergies. A sore throat may just accompany a cold or runny nose, but it may also be an indication of underlying conditions such respiratory tract infections. Sore throat is rather seen as a symptom of respiratory tract disease more than an actual disease. Usually, a sore throat heals on its own. Yet, one might use over-the-counter medications or throat lozenges to treat a sore throat. Try a cough syrup based on the type of cough. Antibiotics are not typically necessary to treat a sore throat. ', 'Y');
